{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bcb92c6cd6a82809", "type": "tool_result", "content": "mains uncertain. Conversely, a large margin between the highest score and the rest gives the attacker high confidence in a successful linkage. Thus, to rigorously evaluate an adversary possessing the full trial vector, we require a metric that explicitly considers the full observed evidence. 5 Proposed Privacy Evaluation Framework To quantify the information an attacker extracts from the observed similarity scores, we propose a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework. This framework processes the two similarity matrices generated in Step 1 ( 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} and 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} ) through three sequential stages: (1) Score Calibration, (2) Inner Aggregation (per-trial local leakage), and (3) Outer Aggregation (global risk profiling). 5.1 Step 1: Calibration (bridging scores to confidence) Raw similarity scores produced by the linkage function L L (e.g., cosine similarities) are domain-dependent and lack intrinsic statistical meaning. To quantify the actual evidentiary weight of an attack, we must calibrate these raw scores into probabilistically meaningful Log-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs). We achieve this in two steps: row-wise normalisation followed by logistic calibration. 5.1.1 Row-wise contextual normalisation. We empirically observe that, particularly for strong anonymisation mechanisms, the absolute magnitude of a similarity score is less informative than its relative distinctiveness among competing enrolment profiles. Therefore, for a given similarity matrix, we first compute the row-wise z-score (often referred to as T-norm in biometrics [ auckenthaler2000score ] ) for each trial i i and enrolment profile j j : s ^ i , j = s i , j − μ i σ i , \\hat{s}_{i,j}=\\frac{s_{i,j}-\\mu_{i}}{\\sigma_{i}}, (2) where μ i \\mu_{i} and σ i \\sigma_{i} are the mean and standard deviation of the raw scores across the N N enrolled identities for trial i i . 5.1.2 Logistic calibration. Next, we map these standardised scores to log-posterior odds using a univariate logistic regression model (Platt scaling [ platt1999probabilistic ] ). Furthermore, because a 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack suffers from extreme class imbalance, where the number of non-mated pairs ( N non-mated N_{\\text{non-mated}} ) in the development set far exceeds the number of mated pairs ( N mated N_{\\text{mated}} ) (there is only one mated score per trial), the posterior probabilities learned by the model are naturally skewed. To isolate the pure evidentiary value (the LLR) independently of this prior distribution, we subtract the prior log-odds from the logistic regression output: LLR i , j = ( w ​ s ^ i , j + b ) − ln ⁡ ( N mated N non-mated ) , \\mathrm{LLR}_{i,j}=(w\\hat{s}_{i,j}+b)-\\ln\\left(\\frac{N_{\\text{mated}}}{N_{\\text{non-mated}}}\\right), (3) where w w and b b are the scalar weight and bias learned from fitting the logistic regression on 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} . Once learned, this calibration pipeline is applied to the evaluation data: 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} undergoes the identical row-wise normalisation before the parameters w w and b b are applied to generate the final evaluation LLRs. 5.2 Step 2: The inner aggregator (local leakage) The Inner Aggregator evaluates the exact information an attacker extracts from a single linkage attempt. For a given trial i i , the attacker attempts to determine the unknown identity of the speaker, modelled as a random variable I ∈ { 1 , 2 , … , N } I\\in\\{1,2,\\dots,N\\} . Let m i m_{i} be the ground-truth index of the target identity. Thus, the event I = m i I=m_{i} represents the scenario where the target identity is correctly determined. Let E i E_{i} represent the biometric evidence observed by the attacker for the trial i i . In practice, this evidence is the vector of LLRs (calibrated similarity scores) comparing the trial against the N N enrolled profiles. By applying the softmax function to the LLRs, the probability of correctly determining the target identity given the evidence is: P ​ ( I = m i ∣ E i ) = p i , m i = exp ⁡ ( LLR i , m i ) ∑ k = 1 N exp ⁡ ( LLR i , k ) . P(I=m_{i}\\mid E_{i})=p_{i,m_{i}}=\\frac{\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,m_{i}})}{\\sum_{k=1}^{N}\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,k})}. (4) Note that in this equation the bias b b and prior log-odds cancel out. Figure 2: Empirical distribution of the posterior probability assigned to the target identity ( p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} ) across a dataset of evaluation trials. The red dotted line denotes the baseline prior probability of a random guess ( 1 / N 1/N , where N = 29 N=29 ). Figure 2 visualises the distribution of these posterior probabilities on real evaluation data. While these probabilities are useful for gaining insight into the attacker's performance, to strictly quantify the privacy loss, we must measure the exact reduction in the attacker's uncertainty. In information theory, the information gained about one event from observing another is defined by Pointwise Mutual Information (PMI) [ fano1961transmission ] . Here, we measure the PMI between the correct linkage ( I = m i I=m_{i} ) and the observed evidence ( E i E_{i} ): PMI ​ ( I = m i ; E i ) = log 2 ⁡ ( P ​ ( I = m i , E i ) P ​ ( I = m i ) ​ P ​ ( E i ) ) . \\mathrm{PMI}(I=m_{i};E_{i})=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{P(I=m_{i},E_{i})}{P(I=m_{i})P(E_{i})}\\right). (5) Estimating the absolute probability of observing a specific continuous biometric vector, P ​ ( E i ) P(E_{i}) , is infeasible. However, by applying the definition of conditional probability, P ​ ( I , E ) = P ​ ( I ∣ E ) ​ P ​ ( E ) P(I,E)=P(I\\mid E)P(E) , the evidence term cancels out: PMI ​ ( I = m i ; E i ) = log 2 ⁡ ( P ​ ( I = m i ∣ E i ) P ​ ( I = m i ) ) . \\mathrm{PMI}(I=m_{i};E_{i})=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{P(I=m_{i}\\mid E_{i})}{P(I=m_{i})}\\right). (6) This derivation shows that the information gained by the attacker is the log-ratio of their posterior belief to their prior belief. A similar conceptual framing of uncertainty reduction is utilised in the SRD framework, which measures the expected information disclosed for each target identity's rank. In contrast, to evaluate the specific evidence observed in a single search, we measure the information disclosed per trial. Assuming no prior biometric evidence, the attacker's initial belief over enrolled identities is uniform: P ​ ( I = m i ) = 1 / N P(I=m_{i})=1/N . By substituting the prior ( 1 / N 1/N ) and posterior ( p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} ) into the PMI formulation, we yield our proposed metric, Local Information Disclosure (LID) , denoted as LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} for trial i i . The term ``local'' emphasises that this disclosure is measured for each individual trial: LID i = log 2 ⁡ ( p i , m i 1 / N ) = log 2 ⁡ ( N ⋅ p i , m i ) . \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{p_{i,m_{i}}}{1/N}\\right)=\\log_{2}(N\\cdot p_{i,m_{i}}). (7) This metric captures the system's behaviour after observing a single trial utterance: • LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 (Positive Disclosure): The evidence increased the attacker's confidence in the target identity above random chance. Privacy is compromised. • LID i = 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=0 (Unlinkability): The prior and posterior match. The evidence provided zero information. • LID i < 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}<0 (Active Deception): The evidence actively misdirected the attacker, lowering their confidence in the target identity to less than random chance. To illustrate, consider a trial compared against N = 6 N=6 enrolments yielding raw scores [ 0.9 , 0.7 , 0.4 , 1.1 , 1.2 , 0.4 ] [0.9,0.7,0.4,\\mathbf{1.1},1.2,0.4] (true target in bold). Row-wise z-normalisation yields [ 0.37 , − 0.27 , − 1.22 , 1.01 , 1.33 , − 1.22 ] [0.37,-0.27,-1.22,\\mathbf{1.01},1.33,-1.22] . Applying calibration (Equation 3 , with w = 1.5 , b = − 1.0 w=1.5,b=-1.0 , and a prior odds ratio of 1 / 5 1/5 ) yields the calibrated log-likelihood ratios [ 1.17 , 0.21 , − 1.23 , 2.12 , 2.61 , − 1.23 ] [1.17,0.21,-1.23,\\mathbf{2.12},2.61,-1.23] . Then the softmax function converts these LLRs to probabilities [ 0.12 , 0.05 , 0.01 , 0.31 , 0.50 , 0.01 ] [0.12,0.05,0.01,\\mathbf{0.31},0.50,0.01] . Although the true target ( 0.31 0.31 ) is not the top-ranked candidate (reflecting attacker uncertainty), this confidence still exceeds the random-guess prior ( 1 / 6 ≈ 0.17 1/6\\approx 0.17 ). Consequently, the trial leaks LID i = log 2 ⁡ ( 6 × 0.31 ) ≈ 0.90 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=\\log_{2}(6\\times 0.31)\\approx 0.90 bits. Plotting the distribution of LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} can reveal key characteristics of the privacy evaluation. For instance, in the specific example shown in Figure 3 , while most trials exhibit active privacy leakage ( LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 ), the negative tail indicates rare but strong instances of deception. Figure 3: Distribution of LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} across evaluation trials. 5.3 Step 3: The outer aggregator (global risk profile) Once LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} is calculated for all T T trials in the evaluation dataset, we obtain a global risk vector ℒ = [ LID 1 , LID 2 , … , LID T ] \\mathcal{L}=[\\mathrm{LID}_{1},\\mathrm{LID}_{2},\\dots,\\mathrm{LID}_{T}] . While visual inspection of this distribution provides insight into system dynamics, benchmarking and systematically comparing different anonymisation architectures requires aggregating this vector into scalar global metrics. The most direct measure of overall privacy loss is the simple average of the trial-level disclosures, which we define as the Average Local Information Disclosure (ALID) : ALID = 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T LID i . \\mathrm{ALID}=\\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathrm{LID}_{i}. (8) However, reporting only ALID \\mathrm{ALID} can be misleading, as extreme instances of active deception ( LID i ≪ 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\ll 0 ) can easily cancel out steady positive disclosures ( LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 ). To prevent global averages from hiding localised vulnerabilities, we must analyse positive and negative disclosures independently. We define the Positive Disclosure Rate (PDR) as the proportion of trials where the attacker gained a statistical advantage over random chance, calculated as PDR = 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T 𝟙 ​ ( LID i > 0 ) \\mathrm{PDR}=\\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathbbm{1}(\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0) . Conversely, the Negative Disclosure Rate (NDR) is defined as the proportion of trials pushing the attacker into uncertainty or misdirection, computed as NDR = 1 − PDR \\mathrm{NDR}=1-\\mathrm{PDR} . Next, we define the Average Positive Disclosure ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} ) to strictly measure the expected privacy leakage in bits only during trials where leakage actually occurred: LID + = 1 T ⋅ PDR ​ ∑ LID i > 0 LID i \\mathrm{LID}^{+}=\\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{PDR}}\\sum_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} . Similarly, we define the Average Negative Disclosure ( LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ) to measure the average strength of the uncertainty introduced during trials yielding negative disclosure: LID − = 1 T ⋅ NDR ​ ∑ LID i ≤ 0 LID i \\mathrm{LID}^{-}=\\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{NDR}}\\sum_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\leq 0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} . This conditional framework provides a transparent view of the system's behaviour. We can then express the overall average local information disclosure (ALID) as the weighted sum of these two opposing forces: ALID = PDR ⋅ LID + + NDR ⋅ LID − . \\mathrm{ALID}=\\mathrm{PDR}\\cdot\\mathrm{LID}^{+}+\\mathrm{NDR}\\cdot\\mathrm{LID}^{-}. (9) By decomposing the global risk in this manner, auditors can explicitly see both the frequency of positive information disclosure and the precise average leakage within those specific trials, fully isolated from the masking effects of the system's deceptive capabilities. Finally, even conditional metrics like LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} represent an expected average, which can mask localised failures. For example, if an anonymisation system protects 99% of users perfectly but leaves 1% of users completely exposed with near-absolute confidence, the system fails GDPR ``singling out'' standards. To ensure strict compliance, we establish the Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max = max ⁡ ( ℒ ) \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}}=\\max(\\mathcal{L}) ), which explicitly measures the largest information disclosure handed to the attacker across the entire evaluation. The summary of these metrics can be found in Table 2 . Table 2: Summary of Proposed Privacy Metrics Metric Name Symbol Equation Description Local Info. Disclosure LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} log 2 ⁡ ( N ⋅ p i , m i ) \\log_{2}(N\\cdot p_{i,m_{i}}) Bits of evidence leading towards the target speaker obtained by observing the i i -th trial utterance. Average LID ALID \\mathrm{ALID} 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T LID i \\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} The average information disclosure among all trials. Positive Disclosure Rate PDR \\mathrm{PDR} 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T 𝟙 ​ ( LID i > 0 ) \\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathbbm{1}(\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0) Proportion of trials where the attacker gains information. Negative Disclosure Rate NDR \\mathrm{NDR} 1 − PDR 1-\\mathrm{PDR} Proportion of trials deceiving the attacker. Average Positive Disc. LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} 1 T ⋅ PDR ​ ∑ LID i > 0 LID i \\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{PDR}}\\sum\\limits_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} Expected privacy leakage (bits) among the positive disclosure trials. Average Negative Disc. LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} 1 T ⋅ NDR ​ ∑ LID i ≤ 0 LID i \\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{NDR}}\\sum\\limits_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\leq 0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} Average magnitude of misleading information obtained across negative disclosure trials. Worst-Case Leakage LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} max ⁡ ( ℒ ) \\max(\\mathcal{L}) Maximum single-trial disclosure (can be used for GDPR ``singling out'' audits). Notation: N N : Number of enrolled identities; p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} : Posterior probability of the correct target identity for trial i i ; T T : Total number of trials in the evaluation dataset; 𝟙 ​ ( ⋅ ) \\mathbbm{1}(\\cdot) : Indicator function yielding 1 if true, 0 otherwise; ℒ \\mathcal{L} : Global risk vector containing all evaluated LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} values. 6 Experiments Figure 4: Complementary Cumulative Distribution Function (CCDF) of the localised information disclosure ( LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} ) across all evaluation trials. The y-axis denotes the percentage of trials exceeding the privacy disclosure indicated on the x-axis. To empirically validate our framework, we execute a comprehensive evaluation adhering to the semi-informed threat model protocols established by VPC 2024 [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] . We fix our evaluation datasets to the standard VPC enrol/trial splits of LibriSpeech dev and eval [ panayotov2015librispeech ] . Following the evaluation methodology established by Chandra et al. [ chandra2026Evaluating ] , we simulate a semi-informed attacker using an ECAPA-TDNN architecture and evaluate a representative selection of anonymisation systems from the 2024 VPC [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] : baselines B3, B4, and B5, alongside systems T8-5, T10-2, T12-5, and T25-1. To bound our evaluation, we additionally include a plain baseline representing unmodified original speech ( f ​ ( x ) = x f(x)=x ) and a random baseline representing theoretical unlinkability (embeddings generated from completely independent random noise). Following the procedure defined in Section 5.1 , we apply row-wise z-normalisation and fit a univariate logistic regression model to the dev matrix to predict ground-truth labels. The learned calibration weights w w and biases b b are detailed in Table 3 . The weight parameter w w serves as a direct indicator of the predictive power of the underlying raw scores, dictating how aggressively the log-likelihood scales as a normalised score deviates from the trial's mean. The plain baseline yields a highly predictive weight ( w = 2.87 w=2.87 ), indicating that a score's relative distinctiveness within a trial strongly correlates with the target identity. Conversely, the random baseline correctly collapses toward zero ( w = 0.03 w=0.03 ). Table 3: Logistic regression calibration parameters learned on the disjoint dev dataset. Experiment 𝐰 \\mathbf{w} 𝐛 \\mathbf{b} B3 1.49 -0.97 B4 1.82 -1.24 B5 1.13 -0.60 T8-5 0.34 -0.05 T10-2 0.90 -0.31 T12-5 0.30 -0.04 T25-1 0.22 -0.02 plain 2.87 -5.92 random 0.03 0.00 These parameters are used to calibrate the eval similarity matrix, and the Inner Aggregator calculates the localised information disclosure ( LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} ) for every individual trial. Figure 4 visualises the Complementary Cumulative Distribution Function (CCDF) of these trial-level disclosures. This representation systematically unmasks the local behaviour of each anonymisation method. The extreme cases are showcased by the plain baseline (where every single trial leaks more than 3.5 3.5 bits of information) and the random baseline (exhibiting a near-vertical collapse at 0 bits, with only marginal deviations due to statistical noise). By mapping the exact proportion of trials at every disclosure level, this visualisation allows auditors to instantly quantify the density of severe localised privacy failures. Table 4: Comparison of baselines (EER, C llr C_{\\text{llr}} ) and average Rank Disclosure (MeanD) against our proposed 1 1 -to- N N metrics: ALID, Positive/Negative Disclosure Rates (PDR/NDR), conditional average disclosures ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} / LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ), and Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} ). Arrows ( ↑ \\uparrow / ↓ \\downarrow ) indicate the direction of increased privacy (e.g., ↓ \\downarrow denotes that a lower value implies better privacy). Experiment EER ( ↑ \\uparrow ) 𝐂 llr \\mathbf{C}_{\\text{llr}} ( ↑ \\uparrow ) MeanD ( ↓ \\downarrow ) ALID ( ↓ \\downarrow ) PDR ( ↓ \\downarrow ) NDR ( ↑ \\uparrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 + \\mathbf{LID}^{+} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 − \\mathbf{LID}^{-} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 max \\mathbf{LID}_{\\text{max}} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) (bits) (bits) (%) (%) (bits) (bits) (bits) B3 0.26 0.75 0.06 1.40 83.9 16.1 1.91 -1.25 4.51 B4 0.29 0.78 0.02 1.79 87.9 12.1 2.19 -1.12 4.74 B5 0.29 0.80 0.02 1.10 79.4 20.6 1.65 -1.02 3.94 T8-5 0.46 0.99 0.06 0.10 65.8 34.2 0.35 -0.37 1.16 T10-2 0.36 0.91 0.52 0.40 76.0 24.0 0.83 -0.97 2.57 T12-5 0.48 0.99 0.02 0.04 63.4 36.6 0.26 -0.33 1.05 T25-1 0.48 0.99 0.05 0.04 63.9 36.1 0.20 -0.25 0.82 plain 0.00 0.01 2.19 4.84 100.0 0.0 4.84 - 4.86 random 0.50 1.00 0.00 0.00 49.9 50.1 0.03 -0.03 0.12 Figure 5: Comparison of Equal Error Rate (EER) against proposed information-theoretic metrics. The divergence of LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} highlights that systems with equivalent global EERs can exhibit different worst-case local vulnerabilities. The scalar global risk profiles generated by the Outer Aggregator are summarised in Table 4 . 4 4 4 Reported EERs differ from official VPC results. The VPC protocol uses specific rules dictating which enrolments are evaluated against which trials, whereas our evaluation exhaustively compared all trials against all enrolments. By isolating the Positive Disclosure Rate (PDR) from the Negative Disclosure Rate (NDR), the framework quantifies the precise directionality of the privacy loss. All evaluated systems (excluding the random baseline) exhibit a PDR exceeding \\qty 63. We observe a positive correlation between the calibration weight w w and the magnitude of the conditional disclosures ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} and LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ). A higher w w indicates that the system's output distributions possess higher variance in biometric confidence. Consequently, systems like B4 not only yield higher expected leakage during successfully linked trials ( LID + = 2.19 \\mathrm{LID}^{+}=2.19 bits) but also generate more convincing false evidence during misdirections ( LID − = − 1.12 \\mathrm{LID}^{-}=-1.12 bits). Expanding upon existing metrics like SRD, this continuous approach allows auditors to measure exactly how much statistical confidence the attacker gains alongside the relative positional ranking. Finally, Figure 5 explicitly contrasts the EER against the proposed metrics, empirically demonstrating the threat model mismatch discussed in Section 4 . Standard global aggregation evaluates systems like T12-5 and T25-1 as indistinguishable, both reporting near-perfect EERs of 0.48 0.48 . However, the 1 1 -to- N N evaluation shows the vulnerabilities of these approaches. By evaluating the Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} ), we observe that these systems expose specific, localised trial utterances to identity linkage ( LID max > 1.0 \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}}>1.0 bit). This confirms that evaluating the amount of evidence within a localised search context is strictly necessary to detect vulnerabilities that global binary thresholds overlook by design. 7 Discussion While the EER remains an effective metric for evaluating general biometric verification performance, our findings demonstrate that relying solely on it for auditing privacy in voice anonymisation is insufficient. We propose a novel privacy metric for evaluating speech anonymisation systems under a realistic 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. Evaluating top-performing systems from the VPC 2024 shows that even the strongest anonymisation methods leak positive information in over \\qty 63 of trials, with worst-case leakage approaching 1 1 bit. Comparing these results against a random noise baseline (with a positive disclosure rate of \\qty 50 and 0.12 0.12 bits maximum leakage) highlights the gap between system performance and statistical unlinkability in 1 1 -to- N N scenarios. Currently, empirical evaluation heavily relies on global metrics like EER, originally designed for 1 1 -to- 1 1 verification. Previous works attempt to adapt these by partitioning datasets by gender, preventing clearly dissimilar voices from artificially skewing non-mated distributions. Our proposed LID framework eliminates the need for such data partitioning. Because LID operates on the full 1 1 -to- N N similarity vector, the presence of a highly similar decoy speaker naturally increases privacy by inflating the denominator of the softmax function, diluting the attacker's confidence. Conversely, adding highly dissimilar speakers to the enrolment database has a negligible impact on the disclosure score, as their calibrated likelihood ratios correctly collapse toward zero. This evidence-based evaluation aligns closely with real-world adversarial behaviour and regulatory definitions of risk, allowing auditors to assess worst-case vulnerabilities without relying on forced-choice assumptions. To define the operational boundaries of our framework, it is important to note that the accuracy of LID relies heavily on the score calibration step. Our current implementation uses logistic regression, which effectively assumes normality in the row-wise z-normalised scores. While this establishes a strong and interpretable baseline, the similarity scores of anonymised speech samples may be skewed. Therefore, a next step would be to explore whether alternative calibration approaches that relax this normality assumption would yield more precise posterior probabilities for these irregular distributions. Framing privacy as a measurable, information-theoretic disclosure introduces several practical research directions. The LID framework can be extended to measure longitudinal leakage by fusing log-likelihood ratios across multiple intercepted sessions [ vauquier2025legally ] , adapted to multi-modal biometric systems [ backstrom2026privacy ] , or evaluated using prior-independent analysis [ nautsch2020privacy ] . Moving beyond global averages to localised evaluation provides the necessary granularity to align theoretical anonymisation research with the strict requirements of real-world privacy system deployment. 8 Acknowledgments We would like to thank the VPC organizers for sharing the anonymised LibriSpeech datasets, and the Audio Security and Privacy Lab at EURECOM, France, for sharing the ECAPA-TDNN model weights. This work was funded by the European Union’s Horizon Europe research and innovation programme under grant agreement No. 101168193. References Experimental support, please view the build logs for errors. Generated by L A T E xml . Instructions for reporting errors We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the methods listed below: Click the \"Report Issue\" ( ) button, located in the page header. Tip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report. Our team has already identified the following issues . We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for all. Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTe", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8ad8ceef-1318-4b82-bdb8-cb0256aa34e5", "uuid": "ef0feac8-b086-4ae8-a984-d8f9d7237db5", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T18:24:24.777Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "mains uncertain. Conversely, a large margin between the highest score and the rest gives the attacker high confidence in a successful linkage. Thus, to rigorously evaluate an adversary possessing the full trial vector, we require a metric that explicitly considers the full observed evidence. 5 Proposed Privacy Evaluation Framework To quantify the information an attacker extracts from the observed similarity scores, we propose a modular, information-theoretic evaluation framework. This framework processes the two similarity matrices generated in Step 1 ( 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} and 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} ) through three sequential stages: (1) Score Calibration, (2) Inner Aggregation (per-trial local leakage), and (3) Outer Aggregation (global risk profiling). 5.1 Step 1: Calibration (bridging scores to confidence) Raw similarity scores produced by the linkage function L L (e.g., cosine similarities) are domain-dependent and lack intrinsic statistical meaning. To quantify the actual evidentiary weight of an attack, we must calibrate these raw scores into probabilistically meaningful Log-Likelihood Ratios (LLRs). We achieve this in two steps: row-wise normalisation followed by logistic calibration. 5.1.1 Row-wise contextual normalisation. We empirically observe that, particularly for strong anonymisation mechanisms, the absolute magnitude of a similarity score is less informative than its relative distinctiveness among competing enrolment profiles. Therefore, for a given similarity matrix, we first compute the row-wise z-score (often referred to as T-norm in biometrics [ auckenthaler2000score ] ) for each trial i i and enrolment profile j j : s ^ i , j = s i , j − μ i σ i , \\hat{s}_{i,j}=\\frac{s_{i,j}-\\mu_{i}}{\\sigma_{i}}, (2) where μ i \\mu_{i} and σ i \\sigma_{i} are the mean and standard deviation of the raw scores across the N N enrolled identities for trial i i . 5.1.2 Logistic calibration. Next, we map these standardised scores to log-posterior odds using a univariate logistic regression model (Platt scaling [ platt1999probabilistic ] ). Furthermore, because a 1 1 -to- N N linkage attack suffers from extreme class imbalance, where the number of non-mated pairs ( N non-mated N_{\\text{non-mated}} ) in the development set far exceeds the number of mated pairs ( N mated N_{\\text{mated}} ) (there is only one mated score per trial), the posterior probabilities learned by the model are naturally skewed. To isolate the pure evidentiary value (the LLR) independently of this prior distribution, we subtract the prior log-odds from the logistic regression output: LLR i , j = ( w ​ s ^ i , j + b ) − ln ⁡ ( N mated N non-mated ) , \\mathrm{LLR}_{i,j}=(w\\hat{s}_{i,j}+b)-\\ln\\left(\\frac{N_{\\text{mated}}}{N_{\\text{non-mated}}}\\right), (3) where w w and b b are the scalar weight and bias learned from fitting the logistic regression on 𝐒 dev \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{dev}} . Once learned, this calibration pipeline is applied to the evaluation data: 𝐒 eval \\mathbf{S}_{\\text{eval}} undergoes the identical row-wise normalisation before the parameters w w and b b are applied to generate the final evaluation LLRs. 5.2 Step 2: The inner aggregator (local leakage) The Inner Aggregator evaluates the exact information an attacker extracts from a single linkage attempt. For a given trial i i , the attacker attempts to determine the unknown identity of the speaker, modelled as a random variable I ∈ { 1 , 2 , … , N } I\\in\\{1,2,\\dots,N\\} . Let m i m_{i} be the ground-truth index of the target identity. Thus, the event I = m i I=m_{i} represents the scenario where the target identity is correctly determined. Let E i E_{i} represent the biometric evidence observed by the attacker for the trial i i . In practice, this evidence is the vector of LLRs (calibrated similarity scores) comparing the trial against the N N enrolled profiles. By applying the softmax function to the LLRs, the probability of correctly determining the target identity given the evidence is: P ​ ( I = m i ∣ E i ) = p i , m i = exp ⁡ ( LLR i , m i ) ∑ k = 1 N exp ⁡ ( LLR i , k ) . P(I=m_{i}\\mid E_{i})=p_{i,m_{i}}=\\frac{\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,m_{i}})}{\\sum_{k=1}^{N}\\exp(\\mathrm{LLR}_{i,k})}. (4) Note that in this equation the bias b b and prior log-odds cancel out. Figure 2: Empirical distribution of the posterior probability assigned to the target identity ( p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} ) across a dataset of evaluation trials. The red dotted line denotes the baseline prior probability of a random guess ( 1 / N 1/N , where N = 29 N=29 ). Figure 2 visualises the distribution of these posterior probabilities on real evaluation data. While these probabilities are useful for gaining insight into the attacker's performance, to strictly quantify the privacy loss, we must measure the exact reduction in the attacker's uncertainty. In information theory, the information gained about one event from observing another is defined by Pointwise Mutual Information (PMI) [ fano1961transmission ] . Here, we measure the PMI between the correct linkage ( I = m i I=m_{i} ) and the observed evidence ( E i E_{i} ): PMI ​ ( I = m i ; E i ) = log 2 ⁡ ( P ​ ( I = m i , E i ) P ​ ( I = m i ) ​ P ​ ( E i ) ) . \\mathrm{PMI}(I=m_{i};E_{i})=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{P(I=m_{i},E_{i})}{P(I=m_{i})P(E_{i})}\\right). (5) Estimating the absolute probability of observing a specific continuous biometric vector, P ​ ( E i ) P(E_{i}) , is infeasible. However, by applying the definition of conditional probability, P ​ ( I , E ) = P ​ ( I ∣ E ) ​ P ​ ( E ) P(I,E)=P(I\\mid E)P(E) , the evidence term cancels out: PMI ​ ( I = m i ; E i ) = log 2 ⁡ ( P ​ ( I = m i ∣ E i ) P ​ ( I = m i ) ) . \\mathrm{PMI}(I=m_{i};E_{i})=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{P(I=m_{i}\\mid E_{i})}{P(I=m_{i})}\\right). (6) This derivation shows that the information gained by the attacker is the log-ratio of their posterior belief to their prior belief. A similar conceptual framing of uncertainty reduction is utilised in the SRD framework, which measures the expected information disclosed for each target identity's rank. In contrast, to evaluate the specific evidence observed in a single search, we measure the information disclosed per trial. Assuming no prior biometric evidence, the attacker's initial belief over enrolled identities is uniform: P ​ ( I = m i ) = 1 / N P(I=m_{i})=1/N . By substituting the prior ( 1 / N 1/N ) and posterior ( p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} ) into the PMI formulation, we yield our proposed metric, Local Information Disclosure (LID) , denoted as LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} for trial i i . The term ``local'' emphasises that this disclosure is measured for each individual trial: LID i = log 2 ⁡ ( p i , m i 1 / N ) = log 2 ⁡ ( N ⋅ p i , m i ) . \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=\\log_{2}\\left(\\frac{p_{i,m_{i}}}{1/N}\\right)=\\log_{2}(N\\cdot p_{i,m_{i}}). (7) This metric captures the system's behaviour after observing a single trial utterance: • LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 (Positive Disclosure): The evidence increased the attacker's confidence in the target identity above random chance. Privacy is compromised. • LID i = 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=0 (Unlinkability): The prior and posterior match. The evidence provided zero information. • LID i < 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}<0 (Active Deception): The evidence actively misdirected the attacker, lowering their confidence in the target identity to less than random chance. To illustrate, consider a trial compared against N = 6 N=6 enrolments yielding raw scores [ 0.9 , 0.7 , 0.4 , 1.1 , 1.2 , 0.4 ] [0.9,0.7,0.4,\\mathbf{1.1},1.2,0.4] (true target in bold). Row-wise z-normalisation yields [ 0.37 , − 0.27 , − 1.22 , 1.01 , 1.33 , − 1.22 ] [0.37,-0.27,-1.22,\\mathbf{1.01},1.33,-1.22] . Applying calibration (Equation 3 , with w = 1.5 , b = − 1.0 w=1.5,b=-1.0 , and a prior odds ratio of 1 / 5 1/5 ) yields the calibrated log-likelihood ratios [ 1.17 , 0.21 , − 1.23 , 2.12 , 2.61 , − 1.23 ] [1.17,0.21,-1.23,\\mathbf{2.12},2.61,-1.23] . Then the softmax function converts these LLRs to probabilities [ 0.12 , 0.05 , 0.01 , 0.31 , 0.50 , 0.01 ] [0.12,0.05,0.01,\\mathbf{0.31},0.50,0.01] . Although the true target ( 0.31 0.31 ) is not the top-ranked candidate (reflecting attacker uncertainty), this confidence still exceeds the random-guess prior ( 1 / 6 ≈ 0.17 1/6\\approx 0.17 ). Consequently, the trial leaks LID i = log 2 ⁡ ( 6 × 0.31 ) ≈ 0.90 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}=\\log_{2}(6\\times 0.31)\\approx 0.90 bits. Plotting the distribution of LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} can reveal key characteristics of the privacy evaluation. For instance, in the specific example shown in Figure 3 , while most trials exhibit active privacy leakage ( LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 ), the negative tail indicates rare but strong instances of deception. Figure 3: Distribution of LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} across evaluation trials. 5.3 Step 3: The outer aggregator (global risk profile) Once LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} is calculated for all T T trials in the evaluation dataset, we obtain a global risk vector ℒ = [ LID 1 , LID 2 , … , LID T ] \\mathcal{L}=[\\mathrm{LID}_{1},\\mathrm{LID}_{2},\\dots,\\mathrm{LID}_{T}] . While visual inspection of this distribution provides insight into system dynamics, benchmarking and systematically comparing different anonymisation architectures requires aggregating this vector into scalar global metrics. The most direct measure of overall privacy loss is the simple average of the trial-level disclosures, which we define as the Average Local Information Disclosure (ALID) : ALID = 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T LID i . \\mathrm{ALID}=\\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathrm{LID}_{i}. (8) However, reporting only ALID \\mathrm{ALID} can be misleading, as extreme instances of active deception ( LID i ≪ 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\ll 0 ) can easily cancel out steady positive disclosures ( LID i > 0 \\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0 ). To prevent global averages from hiding localised vulnerabilities, we must analyse positive and negative disclosures independently. We define the Positive Disclosure Rate (PDR) as the proportion of trials where the attacker gained a statistical advantage over random chance, calculated as PDR = 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T 𝟙 ​ ( LID i > 0 ) \\mathrm{PDR}=\\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathbbm{1}(\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0) . Conversely, the Negative Disclosure Rate (NDR) is defined as the proportion of trials pushing the attacker into uncertainty or misdirection, computed as NDR = 1 − PDR \\mathrm{NDR}=1-\\mathrm{PDR} . Next, we define the Average Positive Disclosure ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} ) to strictly measure the expected privacy leakage in bits only during trials where leakage actually occurred: LID + = 1 T ⋅ PDR ​ ∑ LID i > 0 LID i \\mathrm{LID}^{+}=\\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{PDR}}\\sum_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} . Similarly, we define the Average Negative Disclosure ( LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ) to measure the average strength of the uncertainty introduced during trials yielding negative disclosure: LID − = 1 T ⋅ NDR ​ ∑ LID i ≤ 0 LID i \\mathrm{LID}^{-}=\\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{NDR}}\\sum_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\leq 0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} . This conditional framework provides a transparent view of the system's behaviour. We can then express the overall average local information disclosure (ALID) as the weighted sum of these two opposing forces: ALID = PDR ⋅ LID + + NDR ⋅ LID − . \\mathrm{ALID}=\\mathrm{PDR}\\cdot\\mathrm{LID}^{+}+\\mathrm{NDR}\\cdot\\mathrm{LID}^{-}. (9) By decomposing the global risk in this manner, auditors can explicitly see both the frequency of positive information disclosure and the precise average leakage within those specific trials, fully isolated from the masking effects of the system's deceptive capabilities. Finally, even conditional metrics like LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} represent an expected average, which can mask localised failures. For example, if an anonymisation system protects 99% of users perfectly but leaves 1% of users completely exposed with near-absolute confidence, the system fails GDPR ``singling out'' standards. To ensure strict compliance, we establish the Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max = max ⁡ ( ℒ ) \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}}=\\max(\\mathcal{L}) ), which explicitly measures the largest information disclosure handed to the attacker across the entire evaluation. The summary of these metrics can be found in Table 2 . Table 2: Summary of Proposed Privacy Metrics Metric Name Symbol Equation Description Local Info. Disclosure LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} log 2 ⁡ ( N ⋅ p i , m i ) \\log_{2}(N\\cdot p_{i,m_{i}}) Bits of evidence leading towards the target speaker obtained by observing the i i -th trial utterance. Average LID ALID \\mathrm{ALID} 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T LID i \\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} The average information disclosure among all trials. Positive Disclosure Rate PDR \\mathrm{PDR} 1 T ​ ∑ i = 1 T 𝟙 ​ ( LID i > 0 ) \\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{i=1}^{T}\\mathbbm{1}(\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0) Proportion of trials where the attacker gains information. Negative Disclosure Rate NDR \\mathrm{NDR} 1 − PDR 1-\\mathrm{PDR} Proportion of trials deceiving the attacker. Average Positive Disc. LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} 1 T ⋅ PDR ​ ∑ LID i > 0 LID i \\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{PDR}}\\sum\\limits_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}>0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} Expected privacy leakage (bits) among the positive disclosure trials. Average Negative Disc. LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} 1 T ⋅ NDR ​ ∑ LID i ≤ 0 LID i \\frac{1}{T\\cdot\\mathrm{NDR}}\\sum\\limits_{\\mathrm{LID}_{i}\\leq 0}\\mathrm{LID}_{i} Average magnitude of misleading information obtained across negative disclosure trials. Worst-Case Leakage LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} max ⁡ ( ℒ ) \\max(\\mathcal{L}) Maximum single-trial disclosure (can be used for GDPR ``singling out'' audits). Notation: N N : Number of enrolled identities; p i , m i p_{i,m_{i}} : Posterior probability of the correct target identity for trial i i ; T T : Total number of trials in the evaluation dataset; 𝟙 ​ ( ⋅ ) \\mathbbm{1}(\\cdot) : Indicator function yielding 1 if true, 0 otherwise; ℒ \\mathcal{L} : Global risk vector containing all evaluated LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} values. 6 Experiments Figure 4: Complementary Cumulative Distribution Function (CCDF) of the localised information disclosure ( LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} ) across all evaluation trials. The y-axis denotes the percentage of trials exceeding the privacy disclosure indicated on the x-axis. To empirically validate our framework, we execute a comprehensive evaluation adhering to the semi-informed threat model protocols established by VPC 2024 [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] . We fix our evaluation datasets to the standard VPC enrol/trial splits of LibriSpeech dev and eval [ panayotov2015librispeech ] . Following the evaluation methodology established by Chandra et al. [ chandra2026Evaluating ] , we simulate a semi-informed attacker using an ECAPA-TDNN architecture and evaluate a representative selection of anonymisation systems from the 2024 VPC [ tomashenko2024voiceprivacy ] : baselines B3, B4, and B5, alongside systems T8-5, T10-2, T12-5, and T25-1. To bound our evaluation, we additionally include a plain baseline representing unmodified original speech ( f ​ ( x ) = x f(x)=x ) and a random baseline representing theoretical unlinkability (embeddings generated from completely independent random noise). Following the procedure defined in Section 5.1 , we apply row-wise z-normalisation and fit a univariate logistic regression model to the dev matrix to predict ground-truth labels. The learned calibration weights w w and biases b b are detailed in Table 3 . The weight parameter w w serves as a direct indicator of the predictive power of the underlying raw scores, dictating how aggressively the log-likelihood scales as a normalised score deviates from the trial's mean. The plain baseline yields a highly predictive weight ( w = 2.87 w=2.87 ), indicating that a score's relative distinctiveness within a trial strongly correlates with the target identity. Conversely, the random baseline correctly collapses toward zero ( w = 0.03 w=0.03 ). Table 3: Logistic regression calibration parameters learned on the disjoint dev dataset. Experiment 𝐰 \\mathbf{w} 𝐛 \\mathbf{b} B3 1.49 -0.97 B4 1.82 -1.24 B5 1.13 -0.60 T8-5 0.34 -0.05 T10-2 0.90 -0.31 T12-5 0.30 -0.04 T25-1 0.22 -0.02 plain 2.87 -5.92 random 0.03 0.00 These parameters are used to calibrate the eval similarity matrix, and the Inner Aggregator calculates the localised information disclosure ( LID i \\mathrm{LID}_{i} ) for every individual trial. Figure 4 visualises the Complementary Cumulative Distribution Function (CCDF) of these trial-level disclosures. This representation systematically unmasks the local behaviour of each anonymisation method. The extreme cases are showcased by the plain baseline (where every single trial leaks more than 3.5 3.5 bits of information) and the random baseline (exhibiting a near-vertical collapse at 0 bits, with only marginal deviations due to statistical noise). By mapping the exact proportion of trials at every disclosure level, this visualisation allows auditors to instantly quantify the density of severe localised privacy failures. Table 4: Comparison of baselines (EER, C llr C_{\\text{llr}} ) and average Rank Disclosure (MeanD) against our proposed 1 1 -to- N N metrics: ALID, Positive/Negative Disclosure Rates (PDR/NDR), conditional average disclosures ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} / LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ), and Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} ). Arrows ( ↑ \\uparrow / ↓ \\downarrow ) indicate the direction of increased privacy (e.g., ↓ \\downarrow denotes that a lower value implies better privacy). Experiment EER ( ↑ \\uparrow ) 𝐂 llr \\mathbf{C}_{\\text{llr}} ( ↑ \\uparrow ) MeanD ( ↓ \\downarrow ) ALID ( ↓ \\downarrow ) PDR ( ↓ \\downarrow ) NDR ( ↑ \\uparrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 + \\mathbf{LID}^{+} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 − \\mathbf{LID}^{-} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) 𝐋𝐈𝐃 max \\mathbf{LID}_{\\text{max}} ( ↓ \\downarrow ) (bits) (bits) (%) (%) (bits) (bits) (bits) B3 0.26 0.75 0.06 1.40 83.9 16.1 1.91 -1.25 4.51 B4 0.29 0.78 0.02 1.79 87.9 12.1 2.19 -1.12 4.74 B5 0.29 0.80 0.02 1.10 79.4 20.6 1.65 -1.02 3.94 T8-5 0.46 0.99 0.06 0.10 65.8 34.2 0.35 -0.37 1.16 T10-2 0.36 0.91 0.52 0.40 76.0 24.0 0.83 -0.97 2.57 T12-5 0.48 0.99 0.02 0.04 63.4 36.6 0.26 -0.33 1.05 T25-1 0.48 0.99 0.05 0.04 63.9 36.1 0.20 -0.25 0.82 plain 0.00 0.01 2.19 4.84 100.0 0.0 4.84 - 4.86 random 0.50 1.00 0.00 0.00 49.9 50.1 0.03 -0.03 0.12 Figure 5: Comparison of Equal Error Rate (EER) against proposed information-theoretic metrics. The divergence of LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} highlights that systems with equivalent global EERs can exhibit different worst-case local vulnerabilities. The scalar global risk profiles generated by the Outer Aggregator are summarised in Table 4 . 4 4 4 Reported EERs differ from official VPC results. The VPC protocol uses specific rules dictating which enrolments are evaluated against which trials, whereas our evaluation exhaustively compared all trials against all enrolments. By isolating the Positive Disclosure Rate (PDR) from the Negative Disclosure Rate (NDR), the framework quantifies the precise directionality of the privacy loss. All evaluated systems (excluding the random baseline) exhibit a PDR exceeding \\qty 63. We observe a positive correlation between the calibration weight w w and the magnitude of the conditional disclosures ( LID + \\mathrm{LID}^{+} and LID − \\mathrm{LID}^{-} ). A higher w w indicates that the system's output distributions possess higher variance in biometric confidence. Consequently, systems like B4 not only yield higher expected leakage during successfully linked trials ( LID + = 2.19 \\mathrm{LID}^{+}=2.19 bits) but also generate more convincing false evidence during misdirections ( LID − = − 1.12 \\mathrm{LID}^{-}=-1.12 bits). Expanding upon existing metrics like SRD, this continuous approach allows auditors to measure exactly how much statistical confidence the attacker gains alongside the relative positional ranking. Finally, Figure 5 explicitly contrasts the EER against the proposed metrics, empirically demonstrating the threat model mismatch discussed in Section 4 . Standard global aggregation evaluates systems like T12-5 and T25-1 as indistinguishable, both reporting near-perfect EERs of 0.48 0.48 . However, the 1 1 -to- N N evaluation shows the vulnerabilities of these approaches. By evaluating the Worst-Case Leakage ( LID max \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}} ), we observe that these systems expose specific, localised trial utterances to identity linkage ( LID max > 1.0 \\mathrm{LID}_{\\text{max}}>1.0 bit). This confirms that evaluating the amount of evidence within a localised search context is strictly necessary to detect vulnerabilities that global binary thresholds overlook by design. 7 Discussion While the EER remains an effective metric for evaluating general biometric verification performance, our findings demonstrate that relying solely on it for auditing privacy in voice anonymisation is insufficient. We propose a novel privacy metric for evaluating speech anonymisation systems under a realistic 1 1 -to- N N linkage threat model. Evaluating top-performing systems from the VPC 2024 shows that even the strongest anonymisation methods leak positive information in over \\qty 63 of trials, with worst-case leakage approaching 1 1 bit. Comparing these results against a random noise baseline (with a positive disclosure rate of \\qty 50 and 0.12 0.12 bits maximum leakage) highlights the gap between system performance and statistical unlinkability in 1 1 -to- N N scenarios. Currently, empirical evaluation heavily relies on global metrics like EER, originally designed for 1 1 -to- 1 1 verification. Previous works attempt to adapt these by partitioning datasets by gender, preventing clearly dissimilar voices from artificially skewing non-mated distributions. Our proposed LID framework eliminates the need for such data partitioning. Because LID operates on the full 1 1 -to- N N similarity vector, the presence of a highly similar decoy speaker naturally increases privacy by inflating the denominator of the softmax function, diluting the attacker's confidence. Conversely, adding highly dissimilar speakers to the enrolment database has a negligible impact on the disclosure score, as their calibrated likelihood ratios correctly collapse toward zero. This evidence-based evaluation aligns closely with real-world adversarial behaviour and regulatory definitions of risk, allowing auditors to assess worst-case vulnerabilities without relying on forced-choice assumptions. To define the operational boundaries of our framework, it is important to note that the accuracy of LID relies heavily on the score calibration step. Our current implementation uses logistic regression, which effectively assumes normality in the row-wise z-normalised scores. While this establishes a strong and interpretable baseline, the similarity scores of anonymised speech samples may be skewed. Therefore, a next step would be to explore whether alternative calibration approaches that relax this normality assumption would yield more precise posterior probabilities for these irregular distributions. Framing privacy as a measurable, information-theoretic disclosure introduces several practical research directions. The LID framework can be extended to measure longitudinal leakage by fusing log-likelihood ratios across multiple intercepted sessions [ vauquier2025legally ] , adapted to multi-modal biometric systems [ backstrom2026privacy ] , or evaluated using prior-independent analysis [ nautsch2020privacy ] . Moving beyond global averages to localised evaluation provides the necessary granularity to align theoretical anonymisation research with the strict requirements of real-world privacy system deployment. 8 Acknowledgments We would like to thank the VPC organizers for sharing the anonymised LibriSpeech datasets, and the Audio Security and Privacy Lab at EURECOM, France, for sharing the ECAPA-TDNN model weights. This work was funded by the European Union’s Horizon Europe research and innovation programme under grant agreement No. 101168193. References Experimental support, please view the build logs for errors. Generated by L A T E xml . Instructions for reporting errors We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the methods listed below: Click the \"Report Issue\" ( ) button, located in the page header. Tip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report. Our team has already identified the following issues . We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for all. Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTe", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
